				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">What âBig Thingâ Would Reinvigorate the Democratic Party?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By John Guida			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-25T15:51:28+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 25, 2014 10:51 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 25, 2014 10:51 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/20/opinion/nyto-dems/nyto-dems-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/20/opinion/nyto-dems/nyto-dems-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/20/opinion/nyto-dems/nyto-dems-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003246386" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Alex Wong/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/25/what-big-thing-would-reinvigorate-the-democratic-party/" data-title="What âBig Thingâ Would Reinvigorate the Democratic Party?" data-description="After the midterm debacle, liberals are looking for a compelling national vision.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe party needs to fundamentally retool our thinking.â âWe must speak to the aspirations and the anxieties of every American.âÂ âWe have extraordinarily real and deep problems.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All these statements were uttered by Republicans (Joe Straus, Paul Ryan and Newt Gingrich, respectively) in 2012, according to anÂ <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/politics/as-republicans-ponder-2012-defeat-partys-philosophy-hangs-in-the-balance/2012/12/15/ca030ab4-449b-11e2-8e70-e1993528222d_story.html">election post-mortem</a>Â by Karen Tumulty of The Washington Post.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But in 2014, similar sentiments could just as easily come from Democrats. This year itâs theyÂ who may be, as Yuval Levin at National Review suggests, <a href="//www.nationalreview.com/corner/392147/republican-congress-yuval-levin">intellectually exhausted</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere is less energy in the Democratic coalition,â says <a href="//www.vox.com/2014/11/19/7245775/democrats-new-ideas">Ezra Klein at Vox</a>, than there is among young Republican policy thinkers like Paul Ryan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He adds, âThe Obama administration has been a factory of policy ideas but now its agenda is stalled â and itâs not clear what comes next.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To the frustration of many Democratic voters, key parts of that agenda â raising the minimum wage, for example â easily surpassed the fortunes of the Democratic candidates (who ostensibly, though not necessarily vociferously, supported them) in the midterm elections. State ballot initiatives raising the minimum wage <a href="//time.com/3557834/2014-midterm-elections-minimum-wage/">succeeded</a> in states like Alaska, Arkansas, Nebraska and South Dakota.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As Kevin Baker <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/16/opinion/sunday/delusions-of-the-democrats.html?_r=0">put it</a> in The New York Times, Democrats are in good shape if they can âget people to vote our way even when they agree with us.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nevertheless, Mr. Baker suggests, the party cannot rely on demographics alone and instead should offer, as it has in the past and notably under the âRoosevelt Republic,â âbig things.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Is there a âbig thingâ in the offing? Mr. Klein discussed this with Neera Tanden, the president of the Center for American Progress, who says, broadly speaking, not exactly. She thinks that the thinking on the left has become too small â âas a side-effect of being in power, Democrats had become too obsessed with ideas that could plausibly pass.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Observers often mention inequality as a potential sweeping theme. At <a href="//www.politico.com/story/2014/11/barack-obama-democrats-113016.html">Politico</a>, Edward-Isaac Dovere reports that President Obama has been urged by many on the leftÂ to formulate a vision for addressing the problem. Mr. Dovere quotes a strategist with ties to the White House as saying, âThe best thing he can do is focus on income inequality, and talk about and propose things, and just be a fierce advocate for addressing the economic divide.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Josh Marshall, at <a href="//talkingpointsmemo.com/edblog/forget-the-chatter-this-is-the-democrats-real-problem">Talking Points Memo</a>, sees inequality âÂ as a political matter â as a âloser.â He points to a different âbig, central issueâ for Democrats: âWhat is driving the politics of the country to a mammoth degree is that the vast majority of people in the country no longer have a rising standard of living.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">David Leonhardt, at <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/19/upshot/how-the-great-wage-slowdown-hurts-democrats.html?abt=0002&amp;abg=1">The Upshot</a> for The New York Times, agrees: âThe great wage slowdown of the 21st century â which has left incomes below the level when Mr. Obama took office â is the biggest challenge for the Democratic Party today.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So thatâs, if not the problem, at least a big problem. Unfortunately, as Mr. Marshall (and <a href="//www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum?page=2">others</a>) says, âDemocrats donât have a policy prescription to make that change.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Leonhardt, in <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/11/upshot/the-great-wage-slowdown-looming-over-politics.html">another Upshot article</a>, acknowledges that certain economists could point toÂ a combination of lower health care costs, improved access to education and infrastructure projects as anÂ answer. âBut most Americans would not be able to give a clear answer.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He writesÂ that in the long term, those elements cited by economists â and most important, strong economic growth â should improve income gains.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But in the short term, they wonât. So what might? âThe best hope for doing so, in the immediate future, is probably the oldest and most obvious play in the book: a tax cut,â Mr. Leonhardt says.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet Mr. Klein, in <a href="//www.vox.com/2014/11/12/7204439/is-wage-stagnation-killing-the-democratic-party">another article at Vox</a>, notes that PresidentÂ <span style="color: #4c4e4d;">Obama passed tax cutsâ for the middle â and âthen Democrats got destroyed in the 2010 election. So itâs not clear that middle-class tax cuts are much of a salve.â</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">AndÂ as for an end to wage stagnation as the single âbig thingâ for Democrats, Mr. Klein <a href="//www.vox.com/2014/11/12/7204439/is-wage-stagnation-killing-the-democratic-party">hits a note</a> of caution: âI think the wage slowdown is one of the defining issues of our time. And I would actually like it to be the force driving American politics. But Iâm not sure it is.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He looks ahead for a place to debate these issues and suggests that the 2016 primary battle could be a âvenue for intellectual renewal.â Yet, he notes, Hillary Clinton clearly dominates the field of potential candidates, and this is âlikely to make it unusually difficult for more marginal candidates â who are often the most intellectually exciting participants in primaries â to be heard.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The historian Nicole Hemmer, writing at <a href="//www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/nicole-hemmer/2014/11/11/hillary-clintons-2016-nomination-could-forestall-democratic-policy-debates">U.S. News &amp; World Report</a>, agrees that Democrats âneed a debate about what liberalism is in the 21st century, and what policies best fit the needs of workers whose wages no longer rise as their productivity does.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And, she argues, âthey donât have policy answers, in large part, because when it comes to debates about policy and ideas, the Democratic Party has been moribund since the wrenching foreign policy fights over Iraq. The party has in some ways been a victim of its own success.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In any case, after the midterm elections, Democrats no longer have to worry about being victims of their own success.</p>
